Hooray! These two special needs kitties, Pip & Squeak, have found forever homes! At a very young age, Squeak had to have both of his eyes removed, while Pip lost one. After the surgeries, Pip quickly learned how to be Squeak's eyes for her. She helped guide her to the litter box, helped her eat, and even play. She was her protector. They have been through a lot together, and it is so special to see them staying together in their loving, forever home. #iadopted

Today, Ellie helped me make chocolate pancakes. She was so excited to have us eat them. She kept running around asking us, ‚ÄúIs your tummy SO FULL? Are you soooo happy?!?‚Äù and it kind of just hit me. My child knows what it means to be full and associates food with happy feelings. She knows nothing of real hunger and hopefully never will. Then there‚Äôs this other part where I‚Äôve met SO many hungry kids throughout teaching and my mission trips. Then knowing that my future adopted children might have some sort of struggle with hunger as well, it sort of just blew me away. There‚Äôs no follow up to that thought either. I just soaked in the moment, feeling grateful that I‚Äôve provided for at least one child, and feeling overwhelmed that I can‚Äôt yet do more for my other babe/s. In the meantime, Ellie and I can perfect our pancake recipe so we can serve them to any siblings that may come her way. #ellieardent #momlife #parenthood #adoption #fosterlove #adoptlove #adoptionrocks
